A '''glass melting furnace''' is a [[furnace]] which is designed to melt raw materials into [[glass]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JWvRq9tFOEQC&pg=PA324&dq=%22Glass+melting+furnace%22+is+furnace+designed+to+melt+glass&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwja_p_95LvXAhUrhlQKHZSkAp8Q6AEILTAB#v=onepage&q=%22Glass%20melting%20furnace%22%20is%20furnace%20designed%20to%20melt%20glass&f=false|title=Code of Federal Regulations: 1949-1984|date=1982|publisher=U.S. General Services Administration, National Archives and Records Service, Office of the Federal Register|language=en}}</ref> There are several types of furnace which output a different amount of heat and use different power sources.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Orlov|first=D. L.|last2=Baiburg|first2=L. G.|last3=Tokarev|first3=V. D.|last4=Ignatov|first4=S. V.|last5=Chubinidze|first5=V. A.|date=1986-07-01|title=Combined electric heating of glass in flat-glass furnaces|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF00694861|journal=Glass and Ceramics|language=en|volume=43|issue=7|pages=285–288|doi=10.1007/BF00694861|issn=0361-7610}}</ref> A glass melting furnace is made from a [[refractory material]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0sPVZwG212cC&pg=PA129&dq=Glass+melting+furnace+-wikipedia.org&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjdg7Wq88XXAhXEv1QKHRVFDBkQ6AEILjAC#v=onepage&q=Glass%20melting%20furnace%20-wikipedia.org&f=false|title=Code of Federal Regulations, Title 40, Protection of Environment, PT. 61-62, Revised as of July 1, 2010|last=Register|first=Office of the Federal|date=August 2010|publisher=Government Printing Office|isbn=9780160860300|language=en}}</ref>

