'''Hitaveita Suðurnesja''' was an Icelandic energy company. The largest shareholder was [[Reykjanesbær]]. The company was founded as a geothermal energy firm in the southwest of Iceland in 1974. It built a power plant at [[Svartsengi]] to tap the geothermal energy in the area,<ref name="Development1993">{{cite book|title=Science, Technology and Innovation Policies: Iceland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IrzaAAAAMAAJ|year=1993|publisher=Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development|isbn=978-92-64-13947-3|page=147}}</ref> and was completed in 1976. It was reportedly the first power plant in the world of its kind.<ref>{{cite book|title=Nordic-Baltic-U.S. Almanac|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=100UAQAAMAAJ|year=2006|publisher=Nordic-Baltic-U.S. Almanac, Inc.|page=309}}</ref> It produced and distributed heating and electricity for the entire [[Sudurnes]] region.<ref name="NoStaff2007">{{cite book|title=The Europa World Year Book: 2007|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BR8eTxcLZuoC|date=6 September 2007|publisher=Europa Publications, Routledge|isbn=978-1-85743-413-2|page=2178}}</ref> 

In May 2008, Parliament passed Act no. 58/2008, amending some laws on natural resources and energy. As a result, Hitaveita Suðurnesja was divided into two independent companies, HS Utilities Ltd., distributing electricity, and [[HS Orka]], heating and freshwater, which came into effect on July 1, 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hsorka.is/HSCompanyInfo/financial_statements/HSOrka_Arshlutareikningur2008Q1Q2.pdf |title=Hitaveita Suðurnesja hf. 30. júní 2008 Hitaveita Suðurnesja hf.Samandreginn árshlutareikningur|publisher=Hsorka.is|accessdate=22 May 2014|language=Icelandic}}</ref>

