[[File:Lake County, Illinois oak woodland.jpg|thumb|220px|Oak woodland in [[Lake County, Illinois]].]] An '''oak woodland''' is a [[plant community]] with a tree [[Canopy (biology)|canopy]] dominated by [[oak]]s (''Quercus spp.''). In terms of [[Crown closure|canopy closure]], oak woodlands are intermediate between [[oak savanna]], which is more open, and [[oak forest]], which is more closed.<ref name="widnr">{{cite web |title=Oak Woodland - Wisconsin DNR |url=https://dnr.wi.gov/topic/endangeredresources/communities.asp?mode=detail&Code=CTFOR010WI |website=dnr.wi.gov |publisher=Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources |accessdate=2018-09-22}}</ref> Although the community is named for the dominance of oak trees, the [[understory]] vegetation is often diverse and includes many species of grasses, sedges, forbs, ferns, shrubs, and other plants.
==Examples== * Upper [[Midwestern United States]] oak woodlands dominated by white oak (''[[Quercus alba]]''), burr oak (''[[Quercus macrocarpa|Q. macrocarpa]]''), and black oak (''[[Quercus velutina|Q. velutina]]''), with subdominant canopy species red oak (''[[Quercus rubra|Q. rubra]]'') and shagbark hickory (''[[Carya ovata]]''), with a diverse understory. The community is fire-dependent, shaped by annual, low-intensity fires.<ref name="widnr"/> * Cork oak (''[[Quercus suber]]'') woodlands in the [[Mediterranean Basin|Mediterranean region]]. * Blue oak woodland is found in the inner coast ranges and the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] foothills in [[California]], surrounding the [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]].<ref>C. Michael Hogan (2008) [http://globaltwitcher.auderis.se/artspec_information.asp?thingid=85046 ''Blue Oak: Quercus douglasii'', GlobalTwitcher.com, ed. N. Stromberg] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228073950/http://globaltwitcher.auderis.se/artspec_information.asp?thingid=85046 |date=2012-02-28 }}</ref> Primary species are blue oak (''[[Quercus douglasii|Q. douglasii]]'') and interior live oak (''[[Quercus wislizeni|Q. wizlizeni]]''), with gray pine (''[[Pinus sabiniana]]''), California buckeye (''[[Aesculus californica]]''), and western redbud (''[[Cercis occidentalis]]''). Blue oak woodlands cover about {{convert|2939000|acre|km2}} of the state of California, and of this area about 79%, or {{convert|2322000|acre|km2}}, shows no evidence of past cutting of trees.<ref name="CaliforniaForestResources">{{Cite journal | last1 = Christensen | first1 = Glenn A. | last2 = Campbell | first2 = Sally J. | last3 = Fried| first3 = Jeremy S. | year = 2008 | title = California’s forest resources, 2001–2005: five-year Forest Inventory and Analysis report | url = http://www.fs.fed.us/pnw/publications/gtr763/ | publisher = [[United States Forest Service]], Pacific Northwest Research Station | id = Gen. Tech. Rep. PNW-GTR-763 | pages = 40–46}}</ref>
